TY  - JOUR
T1  - Warranty Signalling and Reputation
AU  - Balachander, Subramanian
Y1  - 2001/09/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.47.9.1282.9783
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.47.9.1282.9783
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1282
EP  - 1289
VL  - 47
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In this paper, we present a signalling-based explanation for the empirical phenomenon that a longer warranty may be offered by a product with lower quality. Our explanation hinges on differences in consumer knowledge about reliability of established and newer products. In a product market where a new entrant competes with an established product, we show that signalling behavior leads to an outcome where the less reliable product may carry the longer warranty.
AB  - In this paper, we present a signalling-based explanation for the empirical phenomenon that a longer warranty may be offered by a product with lower quality. Our explanation hinges on differences in consumer knowledge about reliability of established and newer products. In a product market where a new entrant competes with an established product, we show that signalling behavior leads to an outcome where the less reliable product may carry the longer warranty.
